===============================================================================
@NODE CONTENTS
                                  CONTENTS

This software package consists of the following files:

FReqServer              - the program itself
FReqServer.Guide        - english amigaguide doc
FilterDupeLines         - a tool to filter duplicate lines out of a file
MakeIndex               - a script to create a freqserver-index

@ENDNODE
===============================================================================
@NODE DESCRIPTION
                                  DESCRIPTION

        The FReqServer is a small Fido-Filerequest-Server which, hum,
                            serves Filerequests. :)

            It requires @{"Kickstart 2.04" LINK COPYRIGHT}, @{"Workbench 2.0" LINK COPYRIGHT} or better.

              The FReqServer contains an embedded version id in CBM
  format which can be shown using the Shell command VERSION of Workbench 2.0.

  All program components are tested with Enforcer V37.28 and MungWall V37.55.

@ENDNODE
===============================================================================
@NODE USAGE
                                    USAGE

              Normaly you should start this program from a Mailer,
                but you can use it from your BBS or local, too.

 The CLI-arguments and tooltypes are:
 
 FReqServer:

 FROM/A                     - list of files to search.
 TO/A                       - list of files to send.
 REPORT                     - where to send logdata to.
                              Default: CONSOLE:
 INDEXNAME                  - the basename of your index-files
                              Default: Mail:FReqServer
 MATCHONLY                  - only match & search the filenames, don't search
                              their location, don't write a file.

 MakeIndex:

 DIRS/A                     - dirs where you're files are located.

 First make an assign Mail: (normaly this already exists) then generate the
 index file using the MakeIndex-Script. You can generate a third index-file
 by yourself, which is containing your magics. It has to look like this:

 <MAGIC>
 <NAME>
 <MAGIC>
 <NAME>
    .
    .
    .

 For example:

 FILES
 01730100.lha
 NEWFILES
 Newfiles.lha
 RECENT
 RECENT
 PROTECTOR
 prot17.lha

@ENDNODE
===============================================================================
